fields.byline: By Joseph Moore, Nebraska News Service

fields.text:
Nebraska State Government News

Direct from the source, delivered to your inbox

The Nebraska News Service is the state government news wire service provided by the University of Nebraska-Lincoln College of Journalism and Mass Communications. Our reporters cover a wide range of state government news, including the Nebraska Legislature, the governor's office, state agencies, decisions by Nebraska's Supreme Court, and other news stories as they arise. NNS provides news and information in the form of stories, photos and video. Located in Lincoln, the political heart of the state, we are able to provide our clients with powerful, relevant stories, straight from the source. In turn, our reporters get real-life experience and exposure to the news world. We put particular emphasis on providing content that is relevant to our clients and the communities they serve. Our current client list includes more than 100 newspapers throughout the state with a combined circulation exceeding 280,000, 16 radio stations and 6 television stations.

The Nebraska News Service is staffed by student reporters who submit a resume, cover letter and work samples as a condition for enrollment. The director is Mary Kay Quinlan.
fields.title: Front Page

fields.text:
What is the Nebraska News Service?

The Nebraska News Service was established in 2011 to serve Nebraska news organizations by reporting on state government issues of interest to their audiences. It operates during the fall and spring semesters, but not during the summer. The news service is staffed by student reporters who submit a resume, cover letter and work samples as a condition for enrollment in this three-credit-hour course. The staff changes every semester. The director is Mary Kay Quinlan, Ph.D., associate professor of journalism.

Our Terms of Service

  • We welcome as clients any bona fide news organization, such as newspapers, news websites, radio and television stations. We are unable to serve publications or outlets of any sort that are affiliated with advocacy groups, including political parties and lobbying organizations.
  • We do not require you to publish anything we send you, but if you do publish our reporters' work, please remember that our reporters get paid only in bylines. So we ask that you credit the reporters by name and with the Nebraska News Service identification.
  • We hope you'll feel free to localize stories to suit your needs, but again, please give our reporters byline credit when you use their work.
  • We always welcome story ideas. Please contact the bureau chief at nns.mkquinlan@gmail.com. We cannot promise to cover everything you request, but we'll always do the best we can.
  • If you do choose to publish NNS stories, we'd like to get a complimentary subscription to your publication, as a courtesy, so we can track our efforts. Our mailing address is: Nebraska News Service, c/o Mary Kay Quinlan, 232 Andersen Hall, University of Nebraska-Lincoln, Lincoln, NE 68588-0474.

Our Privacy Policy

We will never use the information you provide us when you register for anything other than serving Nebraska News Service clients, because we want to be nice to you.
fields.title: About Us

fields.text:
Nebraska News Service Reporter Documentation


Welcome to the Nebraska News Service (NNS) content management and distribution system.  

At first glance, the home page appears to look like a normal webpage. Once you are logged in, you will find a content management system that allows you to access existing NNS stories, important information like the NNS Style Guide and Contacts and Tips for various beats, contact information for other NNS clients, reporters and editors, and a place to save content that will eventually be sent to the clients of NNS.

This document contains 2 sections: Getting logged in / managing your user profile, and Creating and Editing Stories and Content.

Getting logged in / managing your user profile

When you visit the home page at nebraskanewsservice.net, prior to being logged in there are only 3 links in the main navigation bar below the logo: About NNS, Login, and Register.  

About NNS contains a brief description of NNS, Terms of Service, and a simple Privacy Policy.  

Login is the front facing user login portal.  

Register is how a new client can sign up and start receiving NNS content.  Registering with the client form provides only limited access to content, and no access to any of the site's functionality.  Reporters should not use this form.

New Reporters need to have a username and password created by an editor.  If you have not been provided with an initial username and password, contact an editor or the NNS director, Mary Kay Quinlan.

Once you have a username and password, you can log in using the Login page.  When you have logged in, if you return to the main page, you will see additional links for Stories, Clients, Reporters and Editors, and on the far right, My Profile and Logout.  Let's look at the My Profile page.

My Profile shows the information currently in the system that identifies you.  This page has two buttons on the right side, Edit my profile, and Change password.  Click on the Edit my profile button to go to the form to edit this information.  The form contains the following fields: First Name, Last Name, Primary Email, Phone, Bio, and Byline.  Fill out all these fields.  Once you have added an email address, you can use this as your username in addition to the username you just used to log in.  Bio is just to tell clients a little about your background, and Byline is what will appear in emails and on each story page, and should be how you want to see yourself credited should a client choose to publish your work.  

The password reset button takes you to a special form where you can reset your password.  It will send an email to the Email address you've listed with instructions to create a new password.

Creating and Editing Stories and Content

Stories contains what you might expect: all stories that have been created by NNS, starting in the Fall of 2013 when the site was in Beta.  

There are 3 links below the main navigation bar: Published Stories, Stories in Progress, and New Story. All stories are listed in date order, with the newest being first. The lists are paginated, and the numbers below the list will switch pages, the arrows move to the first and last pages.

Published Stories is the list of stories that are available to all users, including clients.  These stories are set as published and have likely (but not necessarily) been sent to clients.

Stories in Progress are available to only reporters and editors.  This is where content that's been started but not finished, or potential stories that need additional reporting or vetting, can be created and saved for future use.  

New Story opens the form for starting and editing stories.  When you click "New Story" the form will be blank.  

Creating a new story

A Story does not have to be a traditional text-based story.  Each "Story" represents a unique piece of content, which can include text, multimedia such as audio, video, or slideshows -- saved as videos in YouTube -- and images and documents that are added like a file attachment.  It's best practice to keep each story to one piece of content, and there can be only one file attached to a story. If you have a series of documents, such as a 4-photo series, you need to create a new story for each photo or document in the series.  Titles could be in the form "News Event Photo Series, Image 1", then "News Event Photo Series, Image 2", 3, 4, etc.  I'll go over details for a series of examples, including directions and project specifications for YouTube and typical file sizes and specifications for attachments after we look at the fields included in this form.

Fields

Headline is the title of the story.  When you create the story and save it for the first time, this field is used to automatically create a slug, which is only visible in the URL of the story as an identifier.  You can change the Headline, but doing so will not change the slug that's initially created, so please choose wisely when you initially create a new story.  Avoid headlines like "Temp story name" or other filler text, and always assume that whatever you put here could be seen by a client.

Story Text is the main content field.  This is the content you are sending to users and publishing online.  This can contain up to 50,000 characters.  That's around 5,000 words.  This text field has an HTML code editor -- it's the first button, marked "</>" -- along with other standard paragraph and text formatting tools, buttons to insert online images, YouTube videos, tables, links, and a horizontal rule.  

The "Tags" field adds keywords to help identify the content of this story.  Tags are not required, but it is a good practice, and helps organize content for future use.  Tags are separated by commas, unless there are no commas, then it will separate tags by spaces.  So for example, if you type, "news, tags, something else," you will create 3 tags: "news" "tags" and "something else", but if you type "news tags something else", you will create 4 tags: "news" "tags" "something" and "else". and if you type "news tags something, else" you create 2 tags, "news tags something" and "else".  

The Add Attachment field is a Choose File button that opens a file browser.  Once you select a file, it will show the filename next to the button, long file names will be truncated with an ellipsis. This file isn't actually uploaded until you click Save.  There can be only one attachment per story.  You can replace this document later if you need to add an updated version or replace it with a completely different file.  This field can be left blank.

Editing an existing story

Once you create a story with the required Headline and Story Text and click "Save", this story can now be found in Stories in Progress list.  Both this list and the Published Stories list are in date order, newest first.  Since you will be mainly editing stories in progress, let's start by talking about these stories that have not been published, or have been unpublished.  You can save content that is not published and know that clients will not have access to it, only reporters and editors can view stories in progress.  You must click Save or any work in the window will be lost when you close the browser window.  

If an existing story has been attached to a story, you can replace it or remove it. To remove it and make this field empty, select the checkmark box to the right of the filename. When you click Save, the attachment field will be cleared, leaving it empty.  To replace an existing file, just click Choose File to choose a replacement. When you click Save, the file you choose will replace the current file.

A reporter can also edit a story that has been published, but it's strongly encouraged that you let an editor know if you are doing this, and for what reason.  If a correction needs to be issued, an Editor will need to send the correction to clients.  Once a reporter edits a published story and clicks save, the changes will be live on the website and available for clients who are browsing published content.

Unique Stories in Progress

Some Stories in Progress are unique.  For example, there are Front Page and About Us stories that control the text on the front page and about us page of the website. Do not change these.  

There will be some informational documents, like the NNS Style Guide and a Reporter Handbook, that should only be changed by editors, unless otherwise directed.  

There will also be some running documents with contacts and information about various beats created and edited by former and current reporters.  You can add to these any useful information you acquire for future use by you and by future NNS reporters as a source of institutional knowledge.  Please feel free to contribute to these documents.
